                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/1348a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Warren</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-05-27T17:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 27, 1922—5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>50. The Japanese Chargé d’Affaires called May 25 and asked whether the United
                    States had received any intimation to the effect that Japan is assisting any of
                    the factions in China. He was informed that the Department had received
                    unconfirmed intimations to the effect that Japan is supporting Chang Tso-lin.
                    The Chargé then said that he wished to state that Japan is neutral, has not, and
                    will not give any support to any of the warring factions in China.</p>
                <p>Repeat to Peking as number 133.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hughes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
